How often have we all seen ALL THREE WAVES resisted, frequently 1 or 2?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Based on my reading of the spell data, each wave tests against exactly the same resistance as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, namely fire.  Unless there is a specific penalty for waves of rains, they should therefore be resisted just as often.<br>
<br>
However, it seems like they are resisted more, because there are three separate checks per cast.<br>
<br>
For example, suppose that for a given target the probably of a full hit is 80%, wave or shock, and we ignore partial resists.<br>
<br>
The chance of all three waves hitting for full are .8 x .8 x 8 or .512.  That means about half the time, at least one wave will be resisted, which explains why people think they suck.  Every other cast gets at least one resist.<br>
<br>
However, over time the expected damage is still 80% of full damage per wave, and that is about 500 points per wave, or 1500 points per cast.  Compared to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which is also resisted say 80% of the time, the expected damage is 80% of 1105 or just under 900 points of damage per cast.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Something else to take into consideration is the dmg from SoFB is boosted using focus so in fact your DPM is raised, which is not the case with Sirroco, no?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->From the original post:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> [Sirocco]</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is not effected by the summoned focus damage bracer...However, unlike <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sirocco</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the damage focus bracer does apply <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> [to Shock of Fiery Blades]</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, yielding an average +10% more damage, or 1,105 damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->So yes, I did take that into account.<br>
<br>
The question is though, are rains really resisted more, or is just an illusion arising from the three tests per cast?<br>
And are there limits on the third wave?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usilverbladetheenchanter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Silverblade the Enchanter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magi Draconis</span><br>  Posts: 1594<br> <font color=#333333>(6/20/02 9:08:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1361.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.silverblades-suitcase.com/artofadreamer/3d/excaliburthumb1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ArchMage Spec: Evoke Sirroco vs. Spec: Conj SoFB</span><hr size=1> Nah rains resists are totally screwy, even now at 60 I OFTEN see *all* three waves resisted, and frequently 1 or 2. Regardless of mob's health.<br>
<br>
My own personal beliefs are that:<br>
1) Casting in melee range reduces resists, and I do NOT mean for *melee range only mobs*. I have found giants, because I can get in melee range, resist less.<br>
2) There is a correlation between amount of casts of a spell and resists. TO be exact A new spell will resist much higher until you have used it a while.  Again this is NOT due to level OR skill increases. I showed this to a friend for proff  back when I got Manastorm, we were doing bloodgills in ill omen (PL my bard friend :&gt;). Total green con mobs. My Evoc 3was maxed, I got no xp from this, at start I got <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 100% resists</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  ON GREEN CON MOBS!!!! For about 10 minutes then resists started going down so by the end of 3 hours the resists had changed so that MOST waves hit.<br>
<br>
I strongly suggest folk test those out. When you get a new level with a rain spell, go to a greenie area safe for testing, max evoc skill, start using rain check resists.<br>
Try casting from distance then melee range on large mobs (or even using DDs on mobs in the Hole or Planes where you see highish resists)<br>
<br>
And there *IS* coding that affects range/resists: Mele range only mobs (such as fire giants soem dragons), and there is at least one mob range IS factored into resists, wish I could remember what one *sigh*. So why would it be surprising that range has an effect on resists?<br>
<br>
Redorious<br>
Archmage<br>
